            The real cost of memory isn't embedding — it's the tokens you send
            to the LLM on every chat turn. LLM input tokens cost
            <strong>$2.50–15 / 1M</strong> — that's
            <strong>125–750×</strong> more expensive than embedding
            (<strong>$0.02 / 1M</strong>).
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="math-callout">
          <!-- Primary: LLM token comparison -->
          <div class="math-col naive">
            <div class="math-label">Naive: stuff all memories</div>
            <div class="math-value">2,000+</div>
            <div class="math-desc">
              tokens injected into every LLM call — the entire memory store,
              growing with each session.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="math-col vita">
            <div class="math-label">Vitamem: retrieve relevant</div>
            <div class="math-value">~300</div>
            <div class="math-desc">
              tokens per turn — only the memories that matter, stays flat as
              the store grows.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cost-comparison">
            <div class="cost-row">
              <span class="cost-label">Stuffing over 50 chats:</span>
              <span class="cost-value rose">~100K tokens → $0.25–1.50</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cost-row">
              <span class="cost-label">Retrieval over 50 chats:</span>
              <span class="cost-value teal">~15K tokens → $0.04–0.23</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Secondary: embedding call reduction -->
          <div style="border-top: 1px solid var(--mid); margin-top: 20px; padding-top: 18px; display: flex; gap: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
            <div style="flex: 1; min-width: 200px;">
              <div class="math-label" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">Plus, storage embeddings are batched</div>
              <div style="display: flex; align-items: baseline; gap: 16px;">
                <div>
                  <span class="cost-value rose" style="font-size: 22px;">50</span>
                  <span style="font-size: 12px; opacity: .6;"> calls (naive)</span>
                </div>
                <span style="font-size: 18px; opacity: .4;">→</span>
                <div>
                  <span class="cost-value teal" style="font-size: 22px;">6</span>
                  <span style="font-size: 12px; opacity: .6;"> calls (Vitamem)</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="math-desc" style="margin-top: 6px;">
                ~8× fewer embedding calls — one per extracted fact at dormant
                transition, not per message.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="math-footnote">
            As memory grows from 20 to 200 facts, stuffing cost grows 10×.
            Retrieval stays constant — only the most relevant facts are
